h4. Problem
If a Linker is set in FishEye with a simple regex that matches a single digit, like {noformat}(?i)[#]*(\d+){noformat} some Comments and Commit Messages, *even not matching the regular expression*, get rendered as a combination of the string {{inltokxyzkdtnhgnsbdf}}.


h4. Steps to reproduce
# Add a Linker to FishEye like the following:
{noformat}
<linker><simple regex="(?i)[#]*(\d+)" href="https://www.website.com/${1}" description="Linker"/></linker>
{noformat}
# Add a comment to a review containing only {noformat}"{noformat}
# The comment gets rendered as:
{noformat}
inltokxyzkdtnhgnsbdfinltok 0 inltokxyzkdtnhgnsbdfinltok
{noformat}


h4. Workaround
Avoid the Regex to be matched by single digit. 
In the example provided is sufficient to remove the {{*}}.
{noformat}(?i)[#](\d+){noformat}

as with the {{sed}} 's' command, perl offers some situations where paired delimiters can be replaced with alternatives, provided the alternative chars match each other (pairwise.)
One such case is the 2nd line of the example below.
Fisheye displays the left end of the line correctly, but then renders everything to the right of the 1st '#' (starting with the '#') as a comment.
{code}      my $rcptTo = $obj->{rcpt_to};
      if ($rcptTo =~ qr#next(\d+).*#) {
        $bid = $1;
      }{code}
This is wrong.  The 2 '#'s should be counted as string delimiters, and the content inside (yeah, even embedded, non-escaped single & double quotes!) as a double-quoted string.   So for perl, the contained variables would be highlighted as such, and the rest of the text would be plain string.

