h4. Problem statement
Development panel not showing "Reviews" for Issues linked in the Objectives.

|| JIRA 6.3 and FishEye 3.2.5 || JIRA 6.3 and FishEye 3.6.3 ||
| h4. Steps to Reproduce - part 1
# Create a project in JIRA (e.g. "DEMO) with three issues;
# Create an Application Link between JIRA 6.3.x and FishEye 3.2.5;
# Create a Review in Crucible and add:
#* "DEMO-1" in the title;
#* "DEMO-2" in the "Objectives".
# Navigate to JIRA.  | h4. Steps to Reproduce - part 2:
# Remove the link between JIRA and FishEye 3.2.5;
# Add a link between JIRA 6.3 and FishEye 3.6.x;
# Create a Review in Crucible and add:
#* "DEMO-1" in the title;
#* "DEMO-2" in the "Objectives".|
|  h4. Actual Behavior - part 1:
JIRA will show the review under the 'Reviews' tab on both "DEMO-1" and "DEMO-2". | h4. Actual Behavior - part 2:
JIRA shows the review only on "DEMO-1" on the development panel.|

h4. Expected Behavior:
JIRA would display the review on both  "DEMO-1" and "DEMO-2" when linking to FishEye 3.6.x.

h3. Problem Definition
In Step 2 of JIRA / Crowd Authentication Settings, *Step 2 of 2: Groups to Synchronise from JIRA* if the groups listed are too long they don´t fit in the width of the selection combo and there is no horizontal scroll available.

This makes the group selection hard.

!fishEyeIssue.png|thumbnail!


h3. Suggested Solution
Make the selection combo able to scroll horizontally or to adapt to content width. 


h3. Workaround 
A simple workaround to make things work involves a bit of CSS manipulation:
# Right click on the group selection box and click on {{Inspect Element}}, a panel with some Developer tools should appear.
# Select in the HTML code the line
{code:xml}
<select name="groups" id="groups" class="userSelector multi-select" multiple="multiple">
{code}
# On the right panel (the one containing CSS rules) change the following rules:
#* Change the width from: 
{code}
form.aui select.userSelector {
    width: 150px;
    height: 200px;
}
{code}
to:
{code}
form.aui select.userSelector {
    width: 550px;
    height: 200px;
}
{code}
(i) Adjust the width to the Group name lenght
#* Remove the max-width:
{code}
form.aui .text, form.aui .password, form.aui .textarea, form.aui .select, form.aui .multi-select, form.aui .aui-select2-container .select2-choices {
    border: 1px solid #CCC;
    border-radius: 3.01px;
    box-shadow: 0px 1px 3px #CCC inset;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    font-size: inherit;
    margin: 0px;
    max-width: 250px;
    vertical-align: baseline;
    width: 100%;
{code}
to:
{code}
form.aui .text, form.aui .password, form.aui .textarea, form.aui .select, form.aui .multi-select, form.aui .aui-select2-container .select2-choices {
    border: 1px solid #CCC;
    border-radius: 3.01px;
    box-shadow: 0px 1px 3px #CCC inset;
    box-sizing: border-box;
    font-size: inherit;
    margin: 0px;
   
    vertical-align: baseline;
    width: 100%;
{code}
(!) Please note the missing line {{max-width: 250px;}}

After these two mods you should be able to complete the JIRA Authentication Settings.

In the activity stream, long commit messages are truncated, but somewhat differently to the git recommendation. That is, more than the 1st line is shown.

See http://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit#_discussion
{quote}
Though not required, it’s a good idea to begin the commit message with a single short (less than 50 character) line summarizing the change, followed by a blank line and then a more thorough description. The text up to the first blank line in a commit message is treated as the commit title, and that title is used throughout Git. For example, git-format-patch[1] turns a commit into email, and it uses the title on the Subject line and the rest of the commit in the body.
{quote}

Currently when you configure a SVN repository you need to specify the SVN URL and path. 
The 'Test connection' feature detects a mismatch between the two (for example specifying http://svn/repository as the url, instead of 'http://svn' and 'repository' as the path), but allows the user to continue and add the repository with the wrong config.

Usually such a repository won't be indexed correctly and produce errors like:
{code}
Problem processing revisions from repo %SVN_URL% due to class com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.DbException - Problem getting diff information for rev109
com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.DbException: Problem getting diff information for rev109
{code}
or
{code}
2013-08-21 09:49:01,551 ERROR [InitialPinger1 test_repo] fisheye BaseRepositoryScanner-handleSlurpException - Problem processing revisions from repo test_repo due to class com.cenqua.fisheye.rep.RepositoryClientException - org.tigris.subversion.javahl.ClientException: svn: E170000: URL 'file://localhost/mnt/svn/test_repo/branches/test_branch/test_file.test_file' non-existent in revision 5,233
{code}

This could be avoided by being smarter (either when adding the repository, or during indexing), and automatically discerning between the path and the url.
